# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: melbourne
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] It overtook Rialto Towers and became the tallest building in Melbourne and Australia until August 1991, when 120 Collins Street was completed.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] As of 2022, the tower is the sixth-tallest building in Melbourne and the 11th-tallest building in Australia when measured up to the tallest architectural point, which is the 60 m (200 ft)-tall spire.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] The tower contains 83,000 m2 (890,000 sq ft) of rentable space.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] The floor-to-ceiling height is unusually large for a skyscraper at 2.77 m (9 ft 1 in).
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] The 30 m (98 ft) lifts can reach speeds of 7 m/s (23 ft/s).
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] There are 414 underground car park spaces.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] The building contains double glazed windows with surface coated tempered glass to increase thermal efficiency.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] A large part of the site for 101 was created by demolishing the 26 floor CRA Building, the tallest in the city in the mid 1960s.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] It the first skyscraper to be demolished in the city.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] The owners of 101 Collins have implemented a strategy of buying adjacent properties to safeguard the building's views, particularly towards the south.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] As a result, Flinders Lane has experienced an emergence of new restaurants and bars in older buildings.
[src:melbourne/101-collins-street] 101 Collins Street lends its name to a Yarra Trams stop that is served by routes 11, 12, 48 and 109.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] The building was designed by architectural firm Hassell, in association with Daryl Jackson.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] Structural engineers were Connell Wagner, and mechanical, electrical and fire services engineers were Lincolne Scott.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] 120 Collins Street is a postmodern style building, paying homage to New York City's grand Art Deco buildings, such as the Empire State Building and the Chrysler Building.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] This influence can be seen in the building's granite façade, its setbacks and its central mast.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] When completed in August 1991, the building had a roof height of 220 metres (720 ft) with a 45-metre (148 ft) spire, bringing the total height to 265 metres (869 ft).
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] It was the tallest building in Australia for 14 years until it was surpassed by the Q1 in 2005.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] It remained the tallest building in Melbourne until being surpassed by the residential Eureka Tower in 2006.
[src:melbourne/120-collins-street] As of 2022, it is the fifth-tallest building in Melbourne and the eighth-tallest building in Australia.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] BHP acquired a site at 498–502 Bourke Street in 1948 for £47,250 and earmarked it for demolition to construct a 12 storey office tower for its new headquarters.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The company acquired the Menzies Hotel in 1964 and earmarked its demolition for an even taller tower.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Demolition by Whelan the Wrecker proceeded in 1969.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The Menzies was the city's first luxury hotel and, at the time of its demolition, remained second only to the Hotel Windsor in status as a grand Victorian hotel.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Its demolition had a cultural impact and was seen as a major event in the modernisation of Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The event was painted by artist Ernest Marcuse and is part of the City of Melbourne Art and Heritage Collection.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The construction of BHP House commenced in 1969 and was finished by 1972, by which it was Melbourne's tallest building and its first skyscraper – a high-rise building defined as exceeding 150 metres (490 ft) in height – as well as Australia's second-tallest building behind Australia Square, Sydney.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] BHP House remained Melbourne's tallest building until the completion of the 153-metre-tall (502 ft) Optus Centre in 1975.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Designed in a modern style, BHP House took significant inspiration from contemporary skyscrapers in Chicago.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Consisting of three dominant materials – steel, concrete and glass – the design was promoting the use of steel in Australian construction and sought to establish new national height standards for steel-framed structures.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The building's expressed gridded structure was a clear break from the sheer curtain walls of the 1950s and 1960s, and like the pioneering skyscrapers of Mies van der Rohe, it was designed as a three dimensional sculptural monument, detached from the surrounding cityscape.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] In the architectural field, BHP House is regarded as one of the most notable projects by Yuncken Freeman Architects due to cutting edge techniques for an office building such as flush glazing, minimalist interiors and expressed structural bracing.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Yuncken Freeman carried out a series of experiments for the design proposals of BHP House in the construction processes of their own offices in 1970, located at 411–415 King Street, Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Under the advice of Fazlur Khan, a structural engineer from Skidmore, Owings & Merrill, the design revolves around four basic components to reinvent the tower as a "cantilever" and achieve the properties of a "giant stiff structural tube".
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The four components consist of a steel-framed flooring system, a steel-framed central core, a steel and glass façade, and steel trusses that connect the central core to the façade.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Innovative techniques were employed to lay the foundations of the building – a concrete raft which was poured in a single continuous action.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The weight of the floor structure was reduced by using open-web steel beams and a lightweight layer of concrete.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] Along with cap and belt trusses, this flooring system performed a stiffening effect and allowed structural loads to be transferred down through the central steel-framed core and the outer steel-framed façade, eradicating the need for internal columns and providing flexibility for internal spaces.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The design of the building was also notable for employing the "total energy system", which allowed electrical generation using BHP natural gas.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] It was the first office building in Australia to utilise this technology.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] BHP House set the standard for many subsequent office buildings and led to the change of Melbourne town planning codes which were altered to cater for increased building heights and floor areas.
[src:melbourne/140-william-street-melbourne] The skyscraper measures 41 floors and 152.5 metres in height.
[src:melbourne/1896-melbourne-cup] The **1896 Melbourne Cup** was a two-mile handicap horse race which took place on Tuesday, 3 November 1896.
[src:melbourne/1896-melbourne-cup] Marius Sestier filmed the Melbourne Cup.
[src:melbourne/1896-melbourne-cup] The feature, which consisted of 10 one-minute films shown in chronological order, was premiered at the Princess Theatre, Melbourne on 19 November 1896.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:melbourne/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:melbourne/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:melbourne/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city occupies much of the northern and eastern coastlines of Port Phillip Bay.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] As of June 2025, the population of the city was 5.435 million, or 19% of the population of Australia; It is currently the southernmost city in the world with a population exceeding one million. inhabitants are known as "Melburnians".
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The area of Melbourne has been home to Aboriginal Victorians for over 40,000 years.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Of the five peoples of the Kulin nation, the traditional custodians of the land encompassing Melbourne are the Boonwurrung, Woiwurrung and the Wurundjeri peoples.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1803, a short-lived British penal settlement was established at Port Phillip, then part of the Colony of New South Wales.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne was founded in 1835 with the arrival of free settlers from Van Diemen's Land (modern-day Tasmania).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It was incorporated as a Crown settlement in 1837, and named after the then-Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Declared a city by Queen Victoria in 1847, it became the capital of the newly separated Colony of Victoria in 1851.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] During the 1850s Victorian gold rush, the city entered a lengthy boom period that, by the late 1880s, had transformed it into Australia's, and one of the world's, largest and wealthiest metropolises.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] After the federation of Australia in 1901, Melbourne served as the interim seat of government of the new nation until Canberra became the permanent capital in 1927.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Today, Melbourne is culturally diverse and, among world cities, has the seventh-largest foreign born population.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It is a leading financial centre in the Asia-Pacific region, ranking 28th globally in the 2024 Global Financial Centres Index.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city's eclectic architecture blends Victorian era structures, such as the World Heritage-listed Royal Exhibition Building, with one of the world's tallest skylines.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Additional landmarks include the Melbourne Cricket Ground and the National Gallery of Victoria.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Noted for its cultural heritage, the city gave rise to Australian rules football, Australian impressionism and Australian cinema, and is noted for its street art, live music and theatre scenes.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It hosts major annual sporting events, such as the Australian Grand Prix and the Australian Open, and also hosted the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne ranked as the world's most livable city on the Economist's measure for much of the 2010s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It was also voted the world's best city by *Time Out* in 2026.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne Airport is the second-busiest airport in Australia and the Port of Melbourne is the nation's busiest seaport.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Its main metropolitan rail terminus is Flinders Street station and its main regional rail and road coach terminus is Southern Cross station.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It also has Australia's most extensive freeway network and the largest urban tram network in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Port Phillip area of Melbourne is known in the Boonwurrung/Woiwurrung languages as *Narrm*.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Different parts of Melbourne have different traditional indigenous names, though traditional indigenous area names don't match up exactly with modern council districts.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne city area, near the St Pauls (or possibly St Patricks) cathedrals was called *Geeburr*, Fitzroy area was referred to as *Ngár-go* and Collingwood was known as *Yálla-birr-ang* in the Woiwurrung language.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The wider Port Phillip Bay area is referred to as *Naarm* in the Woiwurrung language and means "the Bay" in the Boonwurrung language.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Aboriginal Australians have lived in the Melbourne area for at least 40,000 years.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] When British colonists arrived in the 19th century, up to 20,000 Kulin people from three distinct language groups – the Wurundjeri, Bunurong and Wathaurong – resided in the area.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It was an important meeting place for the clans of the Kulin nation alliance and a vital source of food and water.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In June 2021, the boundaries between the land of two of the traditional owner groups, the Wurundjeri and Bunurong, were agreed after being drawn up by the Victorian Aboriginal Heritage Council.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The borderline runs across the city from west to east, with the CBD, Richmond and Hawthorn included in Wurundjeri land, and Albert Park, St Kilda and Caulfield on Bunurong land.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] However, this change in boundaries is still disputed by people on both sides of the dispute including N'arweet Carolyn Briggs.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Some sources indicate that the name *Narrm* refers to the area where Melbourne city is built, other sources indicate that Naarm refers to the wider Phillip Bay area in the Woiwurrung language, and Naarm means "the Bay" in the Boonwurrung language.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Narrm means scrub in Eastern Kulin languages which reflects the Creation Story of how the Bay was filled by the creation of the Birrarung (Yarra River).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Before this, the dry Melbourne region extended out into the Bay and the Bay was filled with teatree scrub where boorrimul (emu) and marram (kangaroo) were hunted.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The first British settlement in Victoria, then part of the penal colony of New South Wales, was established by Colonel David Collins in October 1803, at Sullivan Bay, near present-day Sorrento.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The following year, due to a perceived lack of resources, these settlers relocated to Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania) and founded the city of Hobart.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] It would be 30 years before another settlement was attempted.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In May and June 1835, John Batman, a leading member of the Port Phillip Association in Van Diemen's Land, explored the Melbourne area, and later claimed to have negotiated a purchase of 2,400 km2 (600,000 acres) with eight Wurundjeri elders.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Batman selected a site on the northern bank of the Yarra River, declaring that "this will be the place for a village" before returning to Van Diemen's Land.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In August 1835, another group of Vandemonian settlers arrived in the area and established a settlement at the site of the current Melbourne Immigration Museum.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Batman and his group arrived the following month and the two groups ultimately agreed to share the settlement, initially known by the native name of Dootigala.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Batman's Treaty with the Aboriginal elders was annulled by Richard Bourke, the Governor of New South Wales (who at the time governed all of eastern mainland Australia), with compensation paid to members of the association.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1836, Bourke declared the city the administrative capital of the Port Phillip District of New South Wales, and commissioned the first plan for its urban layout, the Hoddle Grid, in 1837.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Previously known under various informal names, the settlement was named Melbourne on 10 April 1837 by Bourke after the British Prime Minister, William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne, whose seat was Melbourne Hall in the market town of Melbourne, Derbyshire.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] That year, the settlement's general post office officially opened with that name.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Between 1836 and 1842, Victorian Aboriginal groups were largely dispossessed of their land by British colonists.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1840, the Superintendent of the Port Phillip District, Charles La Trobe issued a directive to banish Aboriginals from the immediate vicinity of Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This was enforced later that same year by the mass-arrest and imprisonment of hundreds of Indigenous people during the Lettsom raid.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] However, Aboriginal people still managed to continue living near the settlement and by January 1844 there were said to be 675 residing in squalid camps around Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The British Colonial Office had appointed five Aboriginal Protectors for the Aboriginal people of Victoria, in 1839, but their work was nullified by a land policy that favoured squatters who took possession of Aboriginal lands.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] By 1845, fewer than 240 wealthy Europeans held all the pastoral licences then issued in Victoria and became a powerful political and economic force in Victoria for generations to come.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Letters patent of Queen Victoria, issued on 25 June 1847, declared Melbourne a city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] On 1 July 1851, the Port Phillip District separated from New South Wales to become the Colony of Victoria, with Melbourne as its capital.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The discovery of gold in Victoria in mid-1851 sparked a gold rush, and Melbourne, the colony's major port, experienced rapid growth.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Within months, the city's population had nearly doubled from 25,000 to 40,000 inhabitants.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Exponential growth ensued, and by 1865, Melbourne had overtaken Sydney as Australia's most populous city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] An influx of intercolonial and international migrants, particularly from Europe and China, saw the establishment of slums, including Chinatown and a temporary "tent city" on the southern banks of the Yarra.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In the aftermath of the 1854 Eureka Rebellion, mass public support for the plight of the miners resulted in major political changes to the colony, including improvements in working conditions across mining, agriculture, manufacturing and other local industries.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] At least twenty nationalities took part in the rebellion, giving some indication of immigration flows at the time.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] With the wealth brought in from the gold rush and the subsequent need for public buildings, a program of grand civic construction soon began.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The layout of the inner suburbs on a largely one-mile grid pattern, cut through by wide radial boulevards and parklands surrounding the central city, was largely established in the 1850s and 1860s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] These areas rapidly filled with the ubiquitous terrace houses, as well as with detached houses and grand mansions, while some of the major roads developed as shopping streets.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne quickly became a major finance centre, home to several banks, the Royal Mint, and (in 1861) Australia's first stock exchange.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1855, the Melbourne Cricket Club secured possession of its now famous ground, the MCG.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Members of the Melbourne Football Club codified Australian football in 1859, and in 1861, the first Melbourne Cup race was held.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne acquired its first public monument, the Burke and Wills statue, in 1864.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] With the gold rush largely over by 1860, Melbourne continued to grow on the back of continuing gold-mining, as the major port for exporting the agricultural products of Victoria (especially wool) and with a developing manufacturing sector protected by high tariffs.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] An extensive radial railway network spread into the countryside from the late 1850s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Construction started on further major public buildings in the 1860s and 1870s, such as the Supreme Court, Government House, and the Queen Victoria Market.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The central city filled up with shops and offices, workshops, and warehouses.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Large banks and hotels faced the main streets, with fine townhouses in the east end of Collins Street, contrasting with tiny cottages down laneways within the blocks.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Aboriginal population continued to decline, with an estimated 80% total decrease by 1863, due primarily to introduced diseases (particularly smallpox), frontier violence and dispossession of their lands.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The 1880s saw extraordinary growth: consumer confidence, easy access to credit, and steep increases in land prices led to an enormous amount of construction.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] During this "land boom", Melbourne reputedly became the richest city in the world, and the second-largest (after London) in the British Empire.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The decade began with the Melbourne International Exhibition in 1880, held in the large purpose-built Exhibition Building.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] A telephone exchange was established that year, and the foundations of St Paul's were laid.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1881, electric light was installed in the Eastern Market, and a generating station capable of supplying 2,000 incandescent lamps was in operation by 1882.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne cable tramway system opened in 1885 and became one of the world's most extensive systems by 1890.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The establishment of the Melbourne Hydraulic Power Company in 1886 led to the availability of high-pressure piped water, allowing for the installation of hydraulically powered elevators, which led to the construction of the first high-rise buildings in the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The period also saw the huge expansion of a significant radial rail-based transport network throughout the city and suburbs.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's land-boom peaked in 1888, the year it hosted the Centennial Exhibition.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The brash boosterism that had typified Melbourne during that time ended in the early 1890s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The bubble supporting the local finance and property industries burst, resulting in a severe economic depression.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Sixteen small land banks and building societies collapsed, and 133 limited companies went into liquidation.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne financial crisis was a contributing factor to the Australian economic depression of the 1890s and the Australian banking crisis of 1893.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The effects of the depression on the city were profound, with virtually no significant construction until the late 1890s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] At the time of Australia's federation on 1 January 1901, Melbourne became the seat of government of the federated Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The first federal parliament convened on 9 May 1901 in the Royal Exhibition Building, subsequently moving to the Victorian Parliament House, where it sat until it moved to Canberra in 1927.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Governor-General of Australia resided at Government House in Melbourne until 1930, and many major national institutions remained in Melbourne well into the twentieth century.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] During World War II, the city hosted American military forces who were fighting the Empire of Japan, and the government requisitioned the Melbourne Cricket Ground for military use.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In the immediate years after World War II, Melbourne expanded rapidly, its growth boosted by post-war immigration to Australia, primarily from Southern Europe and the Mediterranean.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] While the "Paris End" of Collins Street began Melbourne's boutique shopping and open air cafe cultures, the city centre was seen by many as stale—the dreary domain of office workers—something expressed by John Brack in his famous painting *Collins St., 5 pm* (1955).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Up until the 21st century, Melbourne was considered Australia's "industrial heartland".
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Height limits in the CBD were lifted in 1958, after the construction of ICI House, transforming the city's skyline with the introduction of skyscrapers.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Suburban expansion then intensified, served by new indoor malls beginning with Chadstone Shopping Centre.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The post-war period also saw a major renewal of the CBD and St Kilda Road which significantly modernised the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] New fire regulations and redevelopment saw most of the taller pre-war CBD buildings either demolished or partially retained through a policy of facadism.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Many of the larger suburban mansions from the boom era were also either demolished or subdivided.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] To counter the trend towards low-density suburban residential growth, the government began a series of controversial public housing projects in the inner city by the Housing Commission of Victoria, which resulted in the demolition of many neighbourhoods and a proliferation of high-rise towers.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In later years, with the rapid rise of motor vehicle ownership, the investment in freeway and highway developments greatly accelerated the outward suburban sprawl and declining inner-city population.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Bolte government sought to rapidly accelerate the modernisation of Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Major road projects including the remodelling of St Kilda Junction, the widening of Hoddle Street and then the extensive 1969 Melbourne Transportation Plan changed the face of the city into a car-dominated environment.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Australia's financial and mining booms during 1969 and 1970 resulted in establishment of the headquarters of many major companies (BHP and Rio Tinto, among others) in the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Nauru's then booming economy resulted in several ambitious investments in Melbourne, such as Nauru House.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne remained Australia's main business and financial centre until the late 1970s, when it began to lose this primacy to Sydney.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne experienced an economic downturn between 1989 and 1992, following the collapse of several local financial institutions.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 1992, the newly elected Kennett government began a campaign to revive the economy with an aggressive development campaign of public works coupled with the promotion of the city as a tourist destination with a focus on major events and sports tourism.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] During this period the Australian Grand Prix moved to Melbourne from Adelaide.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Major projects included the construction of a new facility for the Melbourne Museum, Federation Square, the Melbourne Convention & Exhibition Centre, Crown Casino and the CityLink tollway.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Other strategies included the privatisation of some of Melbourne's services, including power and public transport, and a reduction in funding to public services such as health, education and public transport infrastructure.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Since the mid-1990s, Melbourne has maintained significant population and employment growth.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] There has been substantial international investment in the city's industries and property market.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Major inner-city urban renewal has occurred in areas such as Southbank, Port Melbourne, Melbourne Docklands and South Wharf.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne sustained the highest population increase and economic growth rate of any Australian capital city from 2001 to 2004.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] From 2006, the growth of the city extended into "green wedges" and beyond the city's urban growth boundary.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Predictions of the city's population reaching 5 million people pushed the state government to review the growth boundary in 2008 as part of its Melbourne @ Five Million strategy.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 2009, Melbourne was less affected by the Great Recession in comparison to other Australian cities.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Beginning in the 2010s, the State Government of Victoria initiated a number of major infrastructure projects designed to reduce congestion in Melbourne and encourage economic growth, including the Metro Tunnel, the West Gate Tunnel, the Level Crossing Removal Project and the Suburban Rail Loop.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] New urban renewal zones were initiated in inner-city areas like Fisherman's Bend and Arden, while suburban growth continued on the urban periphery in Melbourne's outer west and east in suburbs like Wyndham Vale and Cranbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Middle suburbs like Box Hill became denser as a greater proportion of Melburnians began living in apartments.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] A construction boom resulted in 34 new skyscrapers being built in the central business district between 2010 and 2020.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 2020, Melbourne was classified as an Alpha city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Out of all major Australian cities, Melbourne was the worst affected by the COVID-19 pandemic and spent a long time under lockdown restrictions.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Over the course of its six lockdowns, Melbourne experienced the longest total lockdown period of any city in the world, totalling 262 days.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] While this contributed to a net outflow of migration causing a slight reduction in Melbourne's population over the course of 2020 to 2022, Melbourne's population is projected to reach 6.4 million people by 2033–34.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is in the southeastern part of mainland Australia, within the state of Victoria.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Geologically, it is built on the confluence of Quaternary lava flows to the west, Silurian mudstones to the east, and Holocene sand accumulation to the southeast along Port Phillip.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The southeastern suburbs are situated on the Selwyn fault, which transects Mount Martha and Cranbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The western portion of the metropolitan area lies within the Victorian Volcanic Plain grasslands vegetation community, and the southeast falls in the Gippsland Plains Grassy Woodland zone.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne extends northward through the undulating bushland valleys of the Yarra Valley's tributaries—Moonee Ponds Creek (toward Melbourne Airport), Merri Creek, Darebin Creek and Plenty River.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city reaches southeast through Dandenong to the growth corridor of Pakenham towards West Gippsland.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In the west, it extends along the Maribyrnong River and its tributaries north towards Sunbury.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's major bayside beaches are in the various suburbs along the shores of Port Phillip Bay, in areas like Port Melbourne, Albert Park, St Kilda, Elwood, Brighton, Sandringham, Mentone, Frankston, Altona, Williamstown and Werribee South.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The nearest surf beaches are 85 kilometres (53 mi) south of the Melbourne CBD in the back-beaches of Rye, Sorrento and Portsea.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has, depending on the classification system used, a temperate oceanic (Köppen: *Cfb*) or humid subtropical (Trewartha: *Cf*) climate, with warm summers and cool winters.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is well known for its changeable weather conditions, mainly due to it being located on the boundary of hot inland areas and the cool southern ocean.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This temperature differential is most pronounced in the spring and summer months and can cause strong cold fronts to form.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] These cold fronts can be responsible for varied forms of severe weather from gales to thunderstorms and hail, large temperature drops and heavy rain.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Winters, while exceptionally dry by southern Victorian standards, are often cloudy.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The lack of winter rainfall is because of Melbourne's rain shadowed location between the Otway and Macedon Ranges, which block much of the rainfall arriving from the north and west.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Port Phillip is often warmer than the surrounding oceans or the land mass, particularly in spring and autumn; this can set up a "bay effect rain", where showers are intensified leeward of the bay.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Relatively narrow streams of heavy showers can often affect the same places (usually the eastern suburbs) for an extended period, while the rest of Melbourne and surrounds stays dry.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Overall, the area around Melbourne is, owing to its rain shadow, nonetheless significantly drier than average for southern Victoria.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Within the city and surrounds, rainfall varies widely, from about 425 millimetres (16.7 in) at Little River to 1,250 millimetres (49 in) on the eastern fringe at Gembrook.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne receives 48.6 clear days annually.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Dewpoint temperatures in the summer range from 9.5 to 11.7 °C (49.1 to 53.1 °F).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] These showers are often heavy and can include hail, squalls, and significant drops in temperature, but they often pass through very quickly with a rapid clearing trend to sunny and relatively calm weather and the temperature rising back to what it was before the shower.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This can occur in the space of minutes and can be repeated many times a day, giving Melbourne a reputation for having "four seasons in one day", a phrase that is part of local popular culture.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The highest temperature recorded in Melbourne city was 46.4 °C (115.5 °F), on 7 February 2009.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] While snow is occasionally seen at higher elevations in the outskirts of the city, and dustings were observed in 2020, it has not been recorded in the central business district since 1986.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The sea temperature in Melbourne is warmer than the surrounding ocean during the summer months, and colder during the winter months.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This is predominantly due to Port Phillip Bay being an enclosed and shallow bay that is largely protected from the ocean, resulting in greater temperature variation across seasons.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's urban area is approximately 2,704 kilometres2, the largest in Australia and the 33rd largest in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Hoddle Grid, a grid of streets measuring approximately 1 by 1⁄2 mi (1.61 by 0.80 km), forms the nucleus of Melbourne's central business district (CBD).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The grid's southern edge fronts onto the Yarra River.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] More recent office, commercial and public developments in the adjoining districts of Southbank and Docklands have made these areas into extensions of the CBD in all but name.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] A byproduct of the CBD's layout is its network of lanes and arcades, such as Block Arcade and Royal Arcade.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's CBD has become Australia's most densely populated area, with approximately 19,500 residents per square kilometre, and is home to more skyscrapers than any other Australian city, the tallest being Australia 108, situated in Southbank.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's newest planned skyscraper, Southbank by Beulah (also known as "Green Spine"), has recently been approved for construction and will likely be the tallest building in Australia when completed.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The CBD and surrounds also contain many significant historic buildings such as the Royal Exhibition Building, the Melbourne Town Hall and Parliament House.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Although the area is described as the *centre*, it is not actually the demographic centre of Melbourne at all, due to urban sprawl to the southeast, the demographic centre being located at Camberwell.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is typical of Australian capital cities in that after the turn of the 20th century, it expanded with the underlying notion of a 'quarter acre home and garden' for every family, often referred to locally as the Australian Dream.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This, coupled with the popularity of the private automobile after 1945, led to the auto-centric urban structure now present today in the middle and outer suburbs.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Much of metropolitan Melbourne is accordingly characterised by low-density sprawl, whilst its inner-city areas feature predominantly medium-density, transit-oriented urban forms.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Kilda Road and Southbank areas feature high-density forms.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is often referred to as Australia's garden city, and the state of Victoria is known as *the garden state*.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] There is an abundance of parks and gardens in Melbourne, many close to the CBD with a variety of common and rare plant species amid landscaped vistas, pedestrian pathways and tree-lined avenues.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's parks are often considered the best public parks in all of Australia's major cities.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] There are also many parks in the surrounding suburbs of Melbourne, such as in the municipalities of Stonnington, Boroondara and Port Phillip, southeast of the central business district.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] There are also a number of significant state parks just outside Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The extensive area covered by urban Melbourne is formally divided into hundreds of suburbs (for addressing and postal purposes), and administered as local government areas, 31 of which are located within the metropolitan area.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has minimal public housing and high demand for rental housing, which is becoming unaffordable for many.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Public housing is managed and provided by the Victorian Government's Department of Families, Fairness and Housing, and operates within the framework of the Commonwealth-State Housing Agreement, by which both federal and state governments provide funding for housing.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is experiencing high population growth, generating high demand for housing.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] This housing boom has increased house prices and rents, as well as the availability of all types of housing.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Subdivision regularly occurs in the outer areas of Melbourne, with numerous developers offering house and land packages.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] However, since the release of Melbourne 2030 in 2002, planning policies have encouraged medium-density and high-density development in existing areas with good access to public transport and other services.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] As a result of this, Melbourne's middle and outer-ring suburbs have seen significant brownfields redevelopment.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] On the back of the 1850s gold rush and 1880s land boom, Melbourne became renowned as one of the world's great Victorian-era cities, a reputation that persists due to its diverse range of Victorian architecture.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] High concentrations of well-preserved Victorian-era buildings can be found in the inner suburbs, such as Carlton, East Melbourne and South Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Outstanding examples of Melbourne's built Victorian heritage include the World Heritage-listed Royal Exhibition Building (1880), the General Post Office (1867), Hotel Windsor (1884) and the Block Arcade (1891).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Comparatively little remains of Melbourne's pre-gold rush architecture; St James Old Cathedral (1839) and St Francis' Church (1845) are among the few examples left in the CBD.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Many of the CBD's Victorian boom-time landmarks were also demolished in the decades after World War II, including the Federal Coffee Palace (1888) and the APA Building (1889), one of the tallest early skyscrapers upon completion.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Heritage listings and heritage overlays have since been introduced in an effort to prevent further losses of the city's historic fabric.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In line with the city's expansion during the early 20th century, suburbs such as Hawthorn and Camberwell are defined largely by Federation and Edwardian architectural styles.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The City Baths, built in 1903, are a prominent example of the latter style in the CBD.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The 1926 Nicholas Building is the city's grandest example of the Chicago School style, while the influence of Art Deco is apparent in the Manchester Unity Building, completed in 1932.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city also features the Shrine of Remembrance, which was built as a memorial to the men and women of Victoria who served in World War I and is now a memorial to all Australians who have served in war.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Residential architecture is not defined by a single architectural style, but rather an eclectic mix of large McMansion-style houses (particularly in areas of urban sprawl), apartment buildings, condominiums, and townhouses which generally characterise the medium-density inner-city neighbourhoods.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Freestanding dwellings with relatively large gardens are perhaps the most common type of housing outside inner city Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Victorian terrace housing, townhouses and historic Italianate, Tudor Revival and Neo-Georgian mansions are all common in inner-city neighbourhoods such as Carlton, Fitzroy and further into suburban enclaves like Toorak.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] For much of the 2010s, Melbourne topped *The Economist Intelligence Unit*'s list of the world's most liveable cities, partly due to its cultural attributes.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] State Library Victoria, founded in 1854, is one of the world's oldest free public libraries and, as of 2018, the fourth most-visited library globally.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Fergus Hume's *The Mystery of a Hansom Cab* (1886), the fastest-selling crime novel of the era, is set in Melbourne, as is Australia's best-selling book of poetry, *The Songs of a Sentimental Bloke* (1915) by C.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Contemporary Melbourne authors who have set novels in the city include Peter Carey, Helen Garner and Gerald Murnane.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has Australia's widest range of bookstores, as well as the nation's largest publishing sector.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city also hosts the Melbourne Writers Festival and the Victorian Premier's Literary Awards.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In 2008, it became the second UNESCO City of Literature.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is home to many theatres, eight of which are concentrated in the East End Theatre District, including the Victorian era Athenaeum, Her Majesty's and Princess theatres, as well as the Forum and the Regent.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Other heritage-listed theatres include the avant-garde picture palace The Capitol and St Kilda's Palais Theatre, Australia's largest seated theatre with a capacity of 3,000 people.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Arts Precinct in Southbank is home to Arts Centre Melbourne (which includes the State Theatre and Hamer Hall), as well as the Melbourne Recital Centre, Malthouse Theatre and Southbank Theatre, home of the Melbourne Theatre Company, Australia's oldest professional theatre company.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Australian Ballet, Opera Australia and Melbourne Symphony Orchestra are also based in the precinct.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Many of Melbourne's theatres join the Melbourne Town Hall in hosting the annual Melbourne International Comedy Festival, one of the world's three largest comedy festivals.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has been called "the live music capital of the world"; one study found it has more music venues per capita than any other world city sampled, with 17.5 million patron visits to 553 venues in 2016.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Australia's first global music star, opera singer Nellie Melba, took her stage name from her hometown.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Composer Percy Grainger followed her in becoming the most famous Melburnian of the Edwardian era.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Sidney Myer Music Bowl in Kings Domain hosted the largest crowd ever for a music concert in Australia when an estimated 200,000 attendees saw Melbourne band The Seekers in 1967.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Airing between 1974 and 1987, Melbourne's *Countdown* helped launch the careers of local acts as diverse as AC/DC and Kylie Minogue.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Several distinct post-punk scenes flourished in Melbourne during the late 1970s and early 1980s, including the Little Band scene and St Kilda's Crystal Ballroom scene, which gave rise to Dead Can Dance and Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] More recent independent acts from Melbourne to achieve global recognition include The Avalanches, Gotye and King Gizzard and the Lizard Wizard.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is also regarded as a centre of EDM, and lends its name to the Melbourne Bounce genre and the Melbourne Shuffle dance style, both of which emerged from the city's underground rave scene.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Established in 1861, the National Gallery of Victoria is Australia's oldest and largest art museum, and houses its collection across two sites: NGV International in Southbank and NGV Australia at Federation Square.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Several art movements originated in Melbourne, most famously the Heidelberg School of impressionists, named after a suburb where they camped to paint *en plein air* in the 1880s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Australian tonalists followed in the 1910s, some of whom founded Montsalvat in Eltham, Australia's oldest surviving art colony.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Mid-century Melbourne became a stronghold of figurative modernism through the paintings of the Antipodeans and Angry Penguins; the latter group often met at a pastoral estate in Bulleen, now the Heide Museum of Modern Art.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The city is also home to the Australian Centre for Contemporary Art, as well as numerous independent galleries and artist-run spaces.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In the 2000s, street art proliferated in Melbourne, with Banksy saying its graffiti scene "leads the world", and "laneway galleries" becoming major tourist sites; Hosier Lane for example attracts more Instagram hashtags than some of the city's traditional destinations, like the Melbourne Zoo.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's many public artworks range from the Burke and Wills monument (1865) to the abstract sculpture *Vault* (1978), the latter a popular reference point amongst Melbourne designers.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The oldest film in Australia's National Film and Sound Archive is of the 1896 Melbourne Cup.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne filmmakers spurred Australia's first cinematic boom with *The Story of the Kelly Gang* (1906), shot a quarter century after bushranger Ned Kelly's execution at Old Melbourne Gaol, and since recognised as the world's first feature-length narrative film.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne remained a world leader in film production until the mid-1910s, when several factors, including a ban on bushranger films, contributed to a decades-long decline of the industry.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] A notable film shot and set in Melbourne during this lull was *On the Beach* (1959).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] In the wake of the 1970s Australian Film Revival, many films have been shot and set in Melbourne, including *Mad Max* (1979), *Romper Stomper* (1992), *Chopper* (2000) and *Animal Kingdom* (2010).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne International Film Festival began in 1952 and is one of the world's oldest film festivals.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] The AACTA Awards, Australia's top screen awards, were inaugurated by the festival in 1958.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Docklands Studios Melbourne is the city's largest film and television studio complex and has attracted major international productions.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is also home to the ACMI, the Australian Centre for the Moving Image.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has long been regarded as Australia's sporting capital due to the role it has played in the development of Australian sport, the range and quality of its sporting events and venues, and its high rates of spectatorship and participation.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It is also sometimes dubbed the sporting capital of the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city is also home to 27 professional sports teams competing at the national level, the most of any Australian city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's sporting reputation was recognised in 2016 when, after being ranked as the world's top sports city three times biennially, the Ultimate Sports City Awards in Switzerland named it 'Sports City of the Decade'.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city has hosted a number of major international sporting events, most notably the 1956 Summer Olympics, the first Olympic Games held outside Europe and the United States.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne also hosted the 2006 Commonwealth Games, and is home to several major annual international events, including the Australian Open, the first of the four Grand Slam tennis tournaments.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] First held in 1861 and declared a public holiday for all Melburnians in 1873, the Melbourne Cup is the world's richest handicap horse race, and is known as "the race that stops a nation".
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Formula One Australian Grand Prix has been held at the Albert Park Circuit since 1996.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Cricket was one of the first sports to become organised in Melbourne with the Melbourne Cricket Club forming within three years of settlement.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The club manages one of the world's largest stadiums, the 100,000 capacity Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Established in 1853, the MCG is notable for hosting the first Test match and the first One Day International, played between Australia and England in 1877 and 1971, respectively.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It is also the home of the National Sports Museum, and serves as the home ground of the Victoria cricket team.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] At Twenty20 level, the Melbourne Stars and Melbourne Renegades compete in the Big Bash League.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Australian rules football, Australia's most popular spectator sport, traces its origins to matches played in parklands next to the MCG in 1858.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Its first laws were codified the following year by the Melbourne Football Club, also a founding member, in 1896, of the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's elite professional competition.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Headquartered at Docklands Stadium, the AFL fields a further eight Melbourne-based clubs: Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Hawthorn, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, and the Western Bulldogs.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city hosts up to five AFL matches per round during the home and away season, attracting an average of 40,000 spectators per game.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The AFL Grand Final, traditionally held at the MCG, is the highest attended club championship event in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In soccer, Melbourne is represented in the A-League by Melbourne Victory, Melbourne City FC and Western United FC, and in rugby league it is home to the National Rugby League team, Melbourne Storm.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] North American sports have also gained popularity in Melbourne: basketball sides South East Melbourne Phoenix and Melbourne United play in the NBL; Melbourne Ice and Melbourne Mustangs play in the Australian Ice Hockey League; and Melbourne Aces plays in the Australian Baseball League.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Rowing also forms part of Melbourne's sporting identity, with a number of clubs located on the Yarra River, out of which many Australian Olympians trained.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Netball, the biggest team sport in Australia, is another popular sport throughout the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is represented by the Melbourne Vixens and Melbourne Mavericks in the Suncorp Super Netball League.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a highly diversified economy with particular strengths in finance, manufacturing, research, IT, education, logistics, transportation and tourism.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's suburbs also have the head offices of Coles Group (owner of Coles Supermarkets) and Wesfarmers companies Bunnings, Target, K-Mart and Officeworks, as well as the head office for Australia Post.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city is home to Australia's second busiest seaport, after Port Botany in Sydney.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne Airport provides an entry point for national and international visitors, and is Australia's second busiest airport.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also an important financial centre.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In the 2024 Global Financial Centres Index, Melbourne was ranked as having the 28th most competitive financial centre in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Two of the big four banks, the ANZ and National Australia Bank, are headquartered in Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city has carved out a niche as Australia's leading centre for superannuation (pension) funds, with 40% of the total, and 65% of industry super-funds including the AU$109 billion-dollar Federal Government Future Fund.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city was rated 41st within the top 50 financial cities as surveyed by the MasterCard Worldwide Centers of Commerce Index (2008), second only to Sydney (12th) in Australia.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is Australia's second-largest industrial centre.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It is the Australian base for a number of significant manufacturers including Boeing Australia, truck-makers Kenworth and Iveco, Cadbury as well as Alstom and Jayco, among others.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It is also home to a wide variety of other manufacturers, ranging from petrochemicals and pharmaceuticals to fashion garments, paper manufacturing and food processing.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The south-eastern suburb of Scoresby is home to Nintendo's Australian headquarters.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city also has a research and development hub for Ford Australia, as well as a global design studio and technical centre for General Motors and Toyota Australia respectively.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] CSL, one of the world's top five biotech companies, and Sigma Pharmaceuticals have their headquarters in Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The two are the largest listed Australian pharmaceutical companies.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has an important ICT industry, home to more than half of Australia's top 20 technology companies, and employs over 91,000 people (one third of Australia's ICT workforce), with a turnover of AU$34 billion and export revenues of AU$2.5 billion in 2018.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In addition, tourism also plays an important role in Melbourne's economy, with 10.8 million domestic overnight tourists and 2.9 million international overnight tourists in 2018.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has been attracting an increasing share of domestic and international conference markets.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is the second most visited city in Australia and the seventy-third most visited city in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In 2018, 10.8 million domestic overnight tourists and 2.9 million international overnight tourists visited Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The most visited attractions are Federation Square, Queen Victoria Market, Crown Casino, Southbank, Melbourne Zoo, Melbourne Aquarium, Docklands, National Gallery of Victoria, Melbourne Museum, Melbourne Observation Deck, Arts Centre Melbourne, and the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The State Library of Victoria is the fourth most visited in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Luna Park, a theme park modelled on New York's Coney Island and Seattle's Luna Park, is also a popular destination for visitors.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In its annual survey of readers, the Condé Nast Traveler magazine found that both Melbourne and Auckland were considered the world's friendliest cities in 2014.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's laneways and arcades are of particular importance for the city's tourism–Hosier Lane attracted one million visitors in each year prior to the COVID pandemic.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The laneways of Melbourne have been gentrified and now include prominent displays of street art, which attracts international tourists.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is considered one of the safest world cities for travellers.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a renowned culinary scene that attracts international tourists.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Lygon Street, which runs through the inner-northern suburbs of Melbourne, is a popular dining destination with an abundance of Italian and Greek restaurants that date back to earlier European immigration of the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Food festivals are of particular popularity in Melbourne, many of which are held during early autumn, earning this period the nickname "mad March".
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The most well-known of these events, the Melbourne Food and Wine Festival, takes place over the course of ten days and began in 1993.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also home to many annual events and festivals.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Melbourne International Comedy Festival is held every year in March through to April.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Established in 1987, it is one of the three largest international comedy festivals in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Other notable festivals and events include the Melbourne Flower and Garden Show, the Melbourne International Jazz Festival, the Melbourne Royal Show and the Midsumma Festival.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne added an estimated 105,000 people in 2024-25 and is projected to overtake Sydney as Australia's most populous city sometime between 2032 and 2046.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] After a trend of declining population density since World War II, the city has seen increased density in the inner and western suburbs, aided in part by Victorian Government planning, such as Postcode 3000 and Melbourne 2030, which have aimed to curtail urban sprawl.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] As of 2025, the CBD is the most densely populated area in Australia with more than 43,000 residents per square kilometre, and the inner city suburbs of Carlton, South Yarra, Fitzroy and Collingwood make up Victoria's top five.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] At the 2021 census, 0.7% of Melbourne's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In Greater Melbourne at the 2021 census, 59.9% of residents were born in Australia.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The other most common countries of birth were India (4.9%), Mainland China (3.4%), England (2.7%), Vietnam (1.8%) and New Zealand (1.7%).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] At the time of the 2021 census, 61.1% of Melburnians speak only English at home.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Mandarin (4.3%), Vietnamese (2.3%), Greek (2.1%), Punjabi (2%), and Arabic (1.8%) were the most common foreign languages spoken at home by residents of Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a wide range of religious faiths, the most widely held of which is Christianity.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] This is signified by the city's two large cathedrals—St Patrick's (Roman Catholic), and St Paul's (Anglican).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Both were built in the Victorian era and are of considerable heritage significance as major landmarks of the city.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In recent years, Greater Melbourne's irreligious community has grown to be one of the largest in Australia.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] According to the 2021 Census, persons stating that they had no religion constituted 36.9% of the population.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Christianity was the most popular religious affiliation at 40.1%.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The largest Christian denominations were Catholicism (20.8%) and Anglicanism (5.5%).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The most popular non-Christian religious affiliations were Islam (5.3%), Hinduism (4.1%), Buddhism (3.9%), Sikhism (1.7%) and Judaism (0.9%).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Muslim religious life in Melbourne is centred on about 25 mosques and a number of prayer rooms at university campuses, workplaces and other venues.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] As of 2000, Melbourne had the largest population of Polish Jews and Holocaust survivors in Australia, and the largest number of Jewish institutions.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Of the top twenty high schools in Australia according to the My Choice Schools Ranking, five are in Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] There has also been a rapid increase in the number of International students studying in the city, with Melbourne considered the 5th best student city in the world for studying abroad in the 2026 Best Student Cities ranking by QS.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Eight public universities operate in Melbourne: the University of Melbourne, Monash University, Swinburne University of Technology, Deakin University, Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology (RMIT University), La Trobe University, Australian Catholic University (ACU) and Victoria University (VU).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne universities have campuses all over Australia and some internationally.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Swinburne University and Monash University have campuses in Malaysia, RMIT in Vietnam, with Monash also having a campus in Indonesia and research centres in Prato, Italy, and a joint partnership research academy with IIT Bombay in Mumbai, India.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Both are members of the Group of Eight, a coalition of leading Australian tertiary institutions offering comprehensive and leading education.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] As of 2025 RMIT University is ranked 21st in the world in Architecture.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Swinburne University of Technology, based in the inner-city Melbourne suburb of Hawthorn, was as of 2014 ranked 76th–100th in the world for physics by the Academic Ranking of World Universities.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Deakin University maintains two major campuses in Melbourne and Geelong, and is the third largest university in Victoria.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In recent years, the number of international students at Melbourne's universities has risen rapidly, a result of an increasing number of places being made available for them.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Education in Melbourne is overseen by the Victorian Department of Education (DET), whose role is to 'provide policy and planning advice for the delivery of education'.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Three daily newspapers serve Melbourne: the *Herald Sun* (tabloid), *The Age* (compact) and *The Australian* (national broadsheet).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] There are six primary free-to-air digital television stations operating in Greater Melbourne and Geelong: ABC Victoria, (ABV), SBS Victoria (SBS), Seven Melbourne (HSV), Nine Melbourne (GTV), Ten Melbourne (ATV), C31 Melbourne (MGV) – community television.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Each station (excluding C31) broadcasts a primary channel and several multichannels.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Some digital media companies such as Broadsheet are based in and primarily serve Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Many AM and FM radio stations broadcast to greater Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] These include public (i.e., state-owned ABC and SBS) and community stations.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Many commercial stations are networked-owned: Nova Entertainment owns Nova 100 and Smooth; ARN controls Gold 104.3 and KIIS 101.1; and Southern Cross Austereo runs both Fox and Triple M.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Youth stations include ABC Triple J and youth-run SYN.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Triple J, and community stations PBS and Triple R, strive to play under represented music.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] JOY 94.9 caters for gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender audiences.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] 3MBS and ABC Classic play classical music.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Light FM is a contemporary Christian station.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] AM stations include ABC: ABC Radio Melbourne, Radio National, and News Radio; also Nine Entertainment affiliates 3AW (talk) and Magic (easy listening).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has many community run stations that serve alternative interests, such as 3CR and 3KND (Indigenous).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Many suburbs have low powered community run stations serving local audiences.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The governance of Melbourne is split between the government of Victoria and the 27 cities and four shires that make up the metropolitan area.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] There is no ceremonial or political head of Melbourne, but the Lord Mayor of the City of Melbourne often fulfils such a role as a first among equals.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The local governments are responsible for providing the functions set out in the *Local Government Act* 1989 such as urban planning and waste management.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Most other government services are provided or regulated by the Victorian state government, which governs from Parliament House in Spring Street.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] These include services associated with local government in other countries and include public transport, main roads, traffic control, policing, education above preschool level, health and planning of major infrastructure projects.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Like many Australian cities, Melbourne has a high dependency on the automobile for transport, particularly in the outer suburban areas where the largest number of cars are bought.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] There a total of 3.6 million private vehicles using 22,320 km (13,870 mi) of road in Melbourne, which has one of the highest lengths of road per capita in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The early 20th century saw an increase in popularity of automobiles, resulting in large-scale suburban expansion and a tendency towards the development of urban sprawl—like all Australian cities, inhabitants would live in the suburbs and commute to the city for work.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] By the mid-1950s, there were just under 200 passenger vehicles per 1000 people, and by 2013, there were 600 passenger vehicles per 1000 people.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The road network in Victoria is managed by the Department of Transport and Planning (DTP) who oversee planning and integration.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Maintenance of roads is undertaken by different bodies, depending on the road.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Local roads are maintained by local governments, while secondary and main roads are the responsibility of DTP.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Major national freeways and roads integral to national trade are overseen by the Federal Government.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Today, Melbourne has an extensive network of freeways and arterial roadways.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] These are used by private vehicles, including road freight vehicles, as well as road-based public transport modes like buses and taxis.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Major highways feeding into the city include the Eastern Freeway, Monash Freeway and West Gate Freeway (which spans the large West Gate Bridge).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Other freeways include the Calder Freeway, Tullamarine Freeway, which is the main airport link, and the Hume Freeway, which connects Melbourne to Canberra and Sydney.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's middle suburbs are connected via an orbital freeway, the M80 Ring Road, which will be connected to the Eastern Freeway when the North East Link opens.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Out of Melbourne's twenty declared freeways open or under construction, six are electronic toll roads.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] This includes the M1 and M2 CityLink (which includes the large Bolte Bridge), Eastlink, North East Link, and the West Gate Tunnel.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Apart from Eastlink which is owned and operated by ConnectEast, the toll roads in Melbourne are run by the private company Transurban.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In Melbourne, tollways have blue and yellow signage compared to the green signs used for untolled roads.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has an integrated public transport system based around extensive train, tram, bus and taxi systems.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Flinders Street station was the world's busiest passenger station in 1927 and Melbourne's tram network overtook Sydney's to become the world's largest in the 1940s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] From the 1940s, public transport use in Melbourne declined due to a rapid expansion of the road and freeway network, with the largest declines in tram and bus usage.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] This decline quickened in the early 1990s due to large public transport service cuts.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The operations of Melbourne's public transport system was privatised in 1999 through a franchising model, with operational responsibilities for the train, tram and bus networks licensed to private companies.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] After 1996 there was a rapid increase in public transport patronage due to growth in employment in central Melbourne, with the mode share for commuters increasing to 14.8% and 8.4% of all trips.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] A target of 20% public transport mode share for Melbourne by 2020 was set by the state government in 2006.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Since 2006 public transport patronage has grown by over 20% and a number of projects have commenced aimed at expanding public transport usage.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Melbourne metropolitan rail network dates back to the 1850s gold rush era, and today consists of 227 suburban stations on sixteen lines which radiate from the City Loop, a mostly-underground subway system around the CBD.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Flinders Street station, one of Australia's busiest rail hubs, it serves all lines except the Pakenham, Cranbourne and Sunbury Lines which depart from the nearby connected Town Hall Station, Flinders Street Station remains a prominent Melbourne landmark and meeting place.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The city has rail connections with regional Victorian cities run by V/Line, as well as direct interstate rail services which depart from Melbourne's other major rail terminus, Southern Cross station, in Docklands.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] *The Overland* to Adelaide departs twice a week, while the XPT to Sydney departs twice daily.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In the 2017–2018 financial year, the Melbourne metropolitan rail network recorded 240.9 million passenger trips, the highest ridership in its history.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Many rail lines, along with dedicated lines and rail yards, are also used for freight.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] An assortment of new railways are under construction or have been recently completed in Melbourne.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] A $15 billion new rapid transit heavy rail corridor through the inner city, the Metro Tunnel, opened in late 2025, and became fully operational in February 2026.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It comprises five new stations, twin nine-kilometre tunnels under the CBD connecting the Sunbury line to the Cranbourne/Pakenham line.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The ongoing Level Crossing Removal Project is grade separating much of the network, and rebuilding many older stations.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In June 2022, early works commenced on the Suburban Rail Loop, a 90-kilometre underground automated orbital line through Melbourne's middle suburbs about 12–18 km (7.5–11.2 mi) from the CBD.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] An airport rail connection has commenced with early works in Keilor East.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's tram network dates from the 1880s land boom and, as of 2021, consists of 250 km (155.3 mi) of double track, 475 trams, 25 routes, and 1,763 tram stops, making it the largest in the world.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] In 2017–2018, 206.3 million passenger trips were made by tram.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] About 75 percent of Melbourne's tram network shares road space with other vehicles, while the rest of the network is separated or are light rail routes.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's trams are recognised as iconic cultural assets and a tourist attraction.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Heritage trams operate on the free City Circle route around the CBD.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Trams are free within the central city Free Tram Zone and selected routes run 24-hour service on weekends.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's bus network consists of more than 400 routes which mainly service the outer suburbs and fill the gaps in the network between rail and tram services.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] 114.9 million passenger trips were recorded on Melbourne's buses in 2023–2024, an increase of 15.2 percent on the previous financial year.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne Airport, at Tullamarine, is the city's main international and domestic gateway and second busiest in Australia, with a traffic of over 37 million passengers in 2018–19.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The airport, which comprises four terminals, is the home base for passenger airline Jetstar and cargo airlines Australian airExpress and Team Global Express, and is a major hub for Qantas and Virgin Australia.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Avalon Airport, located between Melbourne and Geelong, is a secondary hub of Jetstar.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It is also used as a freight and maintenance facility.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Buses and taxis are the only forms of public transport to and from the city's main airports.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] A rail link to Tullamarine is planned to open in the 2030s.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Air Ambulance facilities are available for domestic and international transportation of patients.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne also has a significant general aviation airport, Moorabbin Airport in the city's southeast that also handles a small number of passenger flights.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Essendon Airport, which was once the city's main airport, also handles passenger flights, general aviation and some cargo flights.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Ship transport is an important component of Melbourne's transport system.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Port of Melbourne is Australia's largest container and general cargo port and also its busiest, handling more than one-third of the nation's container trade.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The port handled 3.39 million twenty-equivalent units (TEUs) in 2024, making it one of the top five ports in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Station Pier on Port Phillip Bay is the main passenger ship terminal with cruise ships docking there.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Ferries and water taxis run from berths along the Yarra River as far upstream as South Yarra and across Port Phillip Bay.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Among Australian capital cities, Melbourne ties with Canberra in first place for the highest male life expectancy (80.0 years) and ranks second behind Perth in female life expectancy (84.1 years).
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The Victorian Government's Department of Health oversees about 30 public hospitals in the Melbourne metropolitan region and 13 health services organisations.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Major medical, neuroscience and biotechnology research institutions located in Melbourne include the St.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The headquarters of Australian pharmaceutical company CSL Limited is located in the Melbourne Biomedical Precinct in Parkville, which contains over 40 biomedical and research institutions.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] It was announced in 2021 that a new Australian Institute for Infectious Disease would also be built in Parkville.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Other institutions include the Howard Florey Institute, the Murdoch Children's Research Institute, Baker Heart and Diabetes Institute, and the Australian Synchrotron.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Many of these institutions are associated with and located near to universities.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also home to the Royal Children's Hospital and the Monash Children's Hospital.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Water storage and supply for Melbourne is managed by Melbourne Water, which is owned by the Victorian Government.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The organisation is also responsible for management of sewerage and the major water catchments in the region as well as the Wonthaggi desalination plant and North–South Pipeline.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] Water is stored in a series of reservoirs located within and outside the Greater Melbourne area.
[src:melbourne/melbourne-p02] The largest dam, the Thomson River Dam, located in the Victorian Alps, is capable of holding about 60% of Melbourne's water capacity, while smaller dams such as the Upper Yarra Dam, Yan Yean Reservoir, and the Cardinia Reservoir carry secondary supplies.
